window.LEARN_HUB_TECHPLUS = {"tech-01":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><div class=\"lh-tg-summary\">\r\n                            <h3>Chapter snapshot</h3>\r\n                            <p>Master the <strong>IPOS</strong> story (input → processing → output → storage), <strong>bits vs bytes</strong>, <strong>binary / decimal / hex / octal</strong>, <strong>capacity vs throughput</strong> units, <strong>CPU clock</strong>, and a disciplined <strong>troubleshooting</strong> sequence. Exam items often look like “which phase?” or “which unit is larger?”</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>Think of this chapter as the vocabulary of <em>how computers talk about themselves</em>. If you know whether a number measures <strong>size</strong> or <strong>speed</strong>, and whether a symptom needs a <strong>logic</strong> fix or a <strong>process</strong> fix, harder objectives later (networking, security) become easier to place in context.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Computing flow: input, processing, output, storage (IPOS)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Computers look complicated, but almost every task you perform—typing an email, joining a video call, printing a receipt—follows the same story. Data is <em>captured</em>, <em>transformed</em>, <em>shown or sent somewhere</em>, and often <em>kept for later</em>. CompTIA labels that story <strong>IPOS</strong>. Exam writers love short scenarios because they check whether you understand <em>roles</em>, not memorized brand names.</p>\r\n                        <p>Think of <strong>input</strong> as anything that turns a real-world fact into digital signals: keystrokes, touchscreen coordinates, microphone audio, camera frames, barcode scans, or packets arriving from the network. Nothing meaningful happens until those signals exist inside the machine. <strong>Processing</strong> is where meaning is applied—the CPU runs program instructions, the GPU handles massive parallel work like drawing 3D scenes, and mobile <strong>SoCs</strong> combine CPU, GPU, and radios on one chip. <strong>Output</strong> turns results back into something humans or other systems can use: pixels on a display, sound from speakers, paper from a printer, or packets sent to another device. <strong>Storage</strong> answers “what happens when the power cycles or the user comes back tomorrow?” <strong>RAM</strong> holds what you are working on <em>right now</em> but usually empties when power drops; disks, SSDs, and flash keep bits without power; optical discs still appear on exams as a distribution and archive medium.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Walkthrough:</strong> You dictate a note into your phone. The microphone and ADC produce digital audio (<strong>input</strong>). The speech-to-text app runs on the processor (<strong>processing</strong>). You read the transcribed text on screen (<strong>output</strong>). When you tap Save, the note file lands in flash storage (<strong>storage</strong>).\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Input</strong> — Keyboard, mouse, touch, mic, camera, scanner, NFC, NIC receiving data.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Processing</strong> — CPU instructions, GPU rendering, SoC bundles on phones.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Output</strong> — Display, speakers, printer, haptics, network transmit.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Storage</strong> — RAM (volatile workspace), SSD/HDD/NVMe, optical, removable flash.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-note\">\r\n                            <strong>Trick questions:</strong> “The GPU lights up pixels” is still <strong>processing</strong> until those pixels hit the panel; showing the image is <strong>output</strong>. Network <strong>storage</strong> (cloud sync) still ends in a stored copy somewhere—even if you do not see the drive.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Bits, bytes, and number systems</h2>\r\n                        <p>Inside the machine, everything is ultimately <strong>binary</strong>: voltage high or low, gate on or off. A <strong>bit</strong> is that smallest fact. Group eight bits and you get a <strong>byte</strong>, which can represent one of 256 patterns—enough for a small integer, a keyboard character in many encodings, or part of a color. We use <strong>decimal</strong> in daily life because ten fingers; we use <strong>hex</strong> and <strong>octal</strong> in IT because they map cleanly to binary (one hex digit = four bits; one octal digit = three bits), so long strings of bits become shorter to read and type.</p>\r\n                        <p>When you see a <strong>MAC address</strong> like <code>A4:83:E7:12:34:56</code>, each pair is one byte in hex. When a web color is <code>#2A5F9C</code>, each pair is one byte of red, green, blue. You do not have to convert huge numbers by hand on Tech+, but you <em>do</em> need to know <em>what each base is for</em> and that binary place values in a byte run 128, 64, 32, 16, 8, 4, 2, 1.</p>\r\n                        <p>A <strong>nibble</strong> (half a byte, four bits) shows up rarely—know the word in case a question mentions it.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>System</th><th>Base</th><th>Digits / symbols</th><th>Typical use</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Binary</td><td>2</td><td>0–1</td><td>Machine language, masks, addressing</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Decimal</td><td>10</td><td>0–9</td><td>Human-friendly numbers</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Hexadecimal</td><td>16</td><td>0–9, A–F</td><td>MAC addresses, memory dumps, HTML color <code>#RRGGBB</code></td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Octal</td><td>8</td><td>0–7</td><td>Legacy permissions / mainframe contexts</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p>For binary place values in one byte (right to left), positions are 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128. Summing “on” bits gives the decimal value (e.g. <code>1010 0000</code> in one byte = 128 + 32 = 160).</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-key\">\r\n                            <strong>Hex pairs = one byte:</strong> Two hex digits represent 0–255. Example: <code>#FF</code> = 255 decimal. In a color like <code>#336699</code>, each pair is one byte of red, green, blue.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Storage capacity units (KB → PB)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Capacity answers “how much can we hold?”—different from “how fast can we move data?” (throughput, next section). Engineers often use powers of <strong>1024</strong> because memory and addressing are naturally binary: each step up multiplies by 2<sup>10</sup>. Textbooks and some exam items simplify that to <strong>1,000</strong> steps between KB, MB, GB (SI-style). <strong>Both framings appear in the wild.</strong> What you must never miss is the <em>ordering</em>: KB &lt; MB &lt; GB &lt; TB &lt; PB, and that a terabyte-class drive holds vastly more than a gigabyte-class USB stick.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Unit</th><th>Approximate scale</th><th>Intuition</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>KB</td><td>1024 bytes (often rounded to 1,000 in prose)</td><td>Small text file, short email</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>MB</td><td>1024 KB</td><td>Photos, documents, small apps</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>GB</td><td>1024 MB</td><td>OS installs, games, video</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>TB</td><td>1024 GB</td><td>Workstations, NAS, backups</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>PB</td><td>1024 TB</td><td>Data centers, cloud-scale</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-note\">\r\n                            <strong>Why your “1 TB” drive looks smaller in Windows:</strong> Manufacturers often advertise decimal terabytes (10<sup>12</sup> bytes). The OS may report in binary-ish units, so the number <em>looks</em> like less than 1 TB even though the hardware is the same. For the exam, prioritize “which unit is larger?” over decimal precision.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Throughput: bps, Mbps, Gbps (and bytes per second)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Networks sell <strong>speed</strong> in <strong>bits per second</strong> because the physical layer moves bits; ISPs and Wi-Fi specs say <code>Mbps</code> or <code>Gbps</code>. File-copy dialogs often show <strong>MB/s</strong> because humans think in file size (bytes). The bridge between the two is always <strong>divide by 8</strong> when converting from bits per second to bytes per second (and multiply by 8 going the other way).</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Worked idea:</strong> A 1 Gbps (1000 Mbps) Ethernet link can move at most about 125 MB/s of payload in math-class theory. Real life is lower because of protocol overhead, retransmits, and disk limits—but the exam repeatedly checks whether you remembered the <strong>8 bits = 1 byte</strong> step.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>Watch capitalization: <strong>Mb</strong> or <strong>Mbps</strong> = megabits; <strong>MB</strong> = megabytes. Mixing them up is one of the most common wrong answers.</p>\r\n                        <h2>CPU speed: MHz, GHz, and what else matters</h2>\r\n                        <p>The <strong>clock</strong> is a metronome: it does not do work by itself, but it bounds how fast the CPU can step through its internal pipeline. <strong>MHz</strong> is millions of ticks per second; <strong>GHz</strong> is billions. A 3.6 GHz CPU ticks faster than a 2.0 GHz part <em>of the same generation and core layout</em>, but you cannot compare raw GHz across ten years of architecture change—a modern mid-range chip may crush an old “fast” GHz monster because of better branch prediction, cache, and instructions per cycle.</p>\r\n                        <p>For Tech+, know the vocabulary: <strong>multicore</strong> (several CPUs on one package), <strong>multithreading</strong> (often two hardware threads per core), and <strong>cache</strong> (tiny, fast memory next to the core—L1 fastest/smallest, L3 larger/slower). Thermal throttling means the chip slows down if cooling cannot remove heat—another reason a laptop “feels slow” under load.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Troubleshooting methodology (learn the order)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Random fixes waste time and can make things worse (wrong driver, wrong setting, lost data). Professional troubleshooting is <strong>evidence-driven</strong>: you gather clues, form a guess, test that guess in the smallest way possible, then fix and prove the system is healthy again.</p>\r\n                        <p>Imagine a user says “the Internet is broken.” That is not one problem—it is a symptom. You confirm whether <em>one site</em> fails or <em>all</em> sites fail, whether DNS names fail but numeric IPs work, whether only Wi-Fi is down while Ethernet works. Each answer narrows the fault domain (browser vs account vs Wi-Fi vs ISP). That narrowing is what “identify and isolate” means in practice.</p>\r\n                        <ol>\r\n                            <li><strong>Identify the problem</strong> — Question the user; reproduce; note error messages, beeps, LEDs, recent changes; separate one problem from unrelated noise.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Form a theory of probable cause</strong> — Rank likely causes (software vs hardware vs network vs account).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Test the theory</strong> — One change at a time; isolate variables (swap cable, different port, safe mode, ping gateway). If the theory is wrong, undo and try the next theory.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Fix the issue</strong> — Implement the solution (patch, driver, setting, replacement part) based on what you proved.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Verify full functionality and document</strong> — Confirm the symptom is gone and nothing else broke; record symptoms, cause, fix, and any follow-up in the ticket or knowledge base.</li>\r\n                        </ol>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-key\">\r\n                            <strong>Exam angle:</strong> “Try random fixes until it works” is <em>wrong</em>. “Test one theory at a time, then verify” is the professional answer.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Motherboard, firmware, POST, and boot</h2>\r\n                        <p>The <strong>motherboard</strong> is the backplane that ties everything together: CPU socket, RAM slots, chipset, firmware chip, expansion slots (<strong>PCIe</strong>), headers for front-panel buttons, fan connectors, SATA/NVMe/M.2 for storage, and sometimes onboard video or sound. Traces carry high-speed signals—flexing a board, stripped screws, or liquid kills machines faster than “software problems.”</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>BIOS</strong> (older Basic Input/Output System) and <strong>UEFI</strong> (modern firmware interface) both run <em>before</em> the operating system. They initialize hardware, store baseline settings (boot order, date/time, security options), and hand off to a bootloader on disk. UEFI supports larger disks, faster boot, Secure Boot, and a mouse-friendly setup utility—but exam questions still say “BIOS” as a generic term for firmware setup.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>POST</strong> (Power-On Self-Test) is the firmware’s sanity check: RAM presence, CPU, sometimes GPU. Failure often produces <strong>beep codes</strong> (if a speaker is present) or diagnostic LEDs on consumer boards. Random restarts or “no POST” point to power, RAM seating, overheating, or a dead component before you blame Windows.</p>\r\n                        <p>A <strong>CMOS</strong> battery (coin cell) keeps the real-time clock and BIOS settings when AC power is off. If the machine “forgets” time or resets boot order, suspect a weak CMOS battery. <strong>Jumpers</strong> on the board can clear CMOS when a bad overclock or password lock bricks setup—power off first, follow the manual diagram.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Expansion, RAM form factors, and power basics</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>PCIe</strong> slots accept GPUs, NVMe adapters, extra NICs, and capture cards. Lanes (<code>x1</code>, <code>x4</code>, <code>x16</code>) describe electrical width—more lanes for more bandwidth (GPUs want <code>x16</code>). <strong>RAM</strong> for desktops often arrives as <strong>DIMM</strong> modules; laptops use smaller <strong>SODIMM</strong>. Match DDR generation (<strong>DDR4</strong> vs <strong>DDR5</strong>) to the board; mixing speeds usually down-clocks to the slowest stick.</p>\r\n                        <p>The <strong>PSU</strong> label lists wattage and <strong>12V</strong> rail capacity—GPUs care about 12V delivery. Connectors include <strong>24-pin ATX</strong> for the motherboard, <strong>CPU 4/8-pin</strong> near the socket, and <strong>PCIe power</strong> for high-end video cards. Modular PSUs let you detach unused cables for airflow. Never mix modular cables between vendors—pinouts differ and can fry hardware.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Component</th><th>Exam-friendly takeaway</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>CPU</td><td>Executes instructions; needs heatsink/fan or liquid block; thermal paste fills micro-gaps between die and cooler</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>GPU</td><td>Parallel math for graphics/video; has its own RAM (VRAM); may need extra PCIe power leads</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Chipset / PCH</td><td>Hub for USB, SATA, many PCIe lanes—motherboard spec sheet defines limits</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>M.2</td><td>Small SSD form factor; can be SATA or NVMe protocol—NVMe is faster</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Binary drill (one byte):</strong> Bits <code>1100 1010</code> = 128 + 64 + 8 + 2 = <strong>202</strong> decimal. As hex: <code>CA</code> (12 = C, 10 = A). Practice converting your Wi-Fi channel or RAM size into “what does this number mean?” stories, not decimal long division under exam pressure.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-recap\">\r\n                            <div class=\"lh-tg-recap-head\">Exam Essentials recap</div>\r\n                            <h4>Computing &amp; units (Ch.1)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>IPOS:</strong> input → processing on that input → output → long-term storage.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Data units:</strong> one <strong>bit</strong> is 0 or 1; <strong>8 bits = 1 byte</strong>. The book’s essentials use <strong>decimal steps</strong> between larger units (1,000 bytes ≈ 1 KB, 1,000 KB ≈ 1 MB, and so on through TB/PB). CompTIA may use that framing—know it alongside the 1,024-based “binary” style used elsewhere.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Clock:</strong> Hertz = cycles per second; <strong>MHz</strong> = million; <strong>GHz</strong> = billion.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Motherboard</strong> interconnects everything; <strong>CPU</strong> does math/logic; <strong>RAM</strong> is temporary working space (lost at power-off).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>BIOS/UEFI:</strong> runs <strong>POST</strong>, starts boot, stores basics (date/time, RAM size, boot order).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>HDD</strong> = platters + heads; <strong>SSD</strong> = flash; <strong>NVMe</strong> speeds SSD transfers. <strong>Optical:</strong> BD-ROM holds more than DVD-ROM, which holds more than CD-ROM—they don’t replace hard drives.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>GPU</strong> is the video card’s main processor for display.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Expansion roles:</strong> video, sound, <strong>NIC</strong> (network); legacy <strong>modem</strong> over phone lines.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>PSU</strong> converts wall AC to DC for components; <strong>heat</strong> is managed with fans/heatsinks—CPUs need the most attention.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <h4>Troubleshooting (book Ch.12 — fuller sequence)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li>Identify the problem (user, reproduce, isolate).</li>\r\n                                <li>Establish a <strong>theory of probable cause</strong> (question the obvious; use KB/web).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Test the theory</strong>—start simple: cables, power, damage, user error, reboot.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Plan</strong> then <strong>implement</strong> the fix (one machine or many).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Verify</strong> full functionality; add preventive measures if needed.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Document</strong> findings, actions, outcomes.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <p class=\"src\">High-yield bullets aligned with typical FC0-U71 training topics—use with the lessons above.</p>\r\n                        </div></div>","tech-02":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><div class=\"lh-tg-summary\">\r\n                            <h3>Chapter snapshot</h3>\r\n                            <p>Tech+ expects you to recognize devices, internal parts, storage and connectivity, <strong>basic maintenance</strong>, and how a typical <strong>Windows workstation</strong> plus <strong>home/small-office network</strong> fits together. Pair this chapter with hands-on: plug in a printer, read a cable jacket label, open Task Manager.</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>This chapter connects the <em>physical world</em> (ports, printers, Wi-Fi radios) to the <em>logical world</em> (IP addresses, cloud VMs). Read it once straight through to see how data moves from your keyboard to a router to the Internet and maybe to someone else’s SaaS app—then revisit sections that match your weakest objectives.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Workstation setup (what “good” looks like)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Setting up a workstation is more than plugging in cables—it is making a system <em>stable, updatable, and safe for daily use</em>. CompTIA expects you to think like someone who could deploy a desk at a small office or help a family member at home.</p>\r\n                        <p>Start with <strong>power quality</strong>: a surge strip is not the same as a <strong>UPS</strong>. A UPS gives you minutes to save work when utility power drops and often conditions noisy power. Route cables so nothing kinks, trips people, or blocks vents. Install Windows (or join a domain), create a <strong>standard user</strong> for everyday tasks, and reserve administrator elevation for installs and fixes—malware loves an always-admin account.</p>\r\n                        <p>Confirm <strong>Device Manager</strong> is clean (no yellow bangs), Ethernet or Wi-Fi gets an address, and <strong>Windows Update</strong> has run at least once. Attach monitor, keyboard, mouse, and any dock or USB hub; verify sound and webcam in Settings before you call the job done.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Devices &amp; internal components</h2>\r\n                        <p>Form factors exist because different jobs need different balances of <strong>power, portability, cost, and upgrade path</strong>. A tower desktop has room for full-size GPUs and multiple drives; a laptop trades expansion for mobility; a thin client assumes the “real computer” lives in the data center; a server prioritizes uptime, remote management, and redundant parts.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Form factor</th><th>Notes for the exam</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Desktop / tower / SFF</td><td>Modular upgrades (GPU, RAM, storage); separate monitor</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Laptop / 2-in-1</td><td>Integrated display; battery; mobile NICs; often soldered RAM/SSD on ultrabooks</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Tablet / smartphone</td><td>Touch-first; ARM SoCs common; cellular + Wi-Fi</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Server</td><td>Reliability, redundancy, remote management (iLO/iDRAC concepts)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Thin client</td><td>Minimal local OS; relies on remote session / VDI / cloud app</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>IoT / embedded</td><td>Sensors, limited UI, firmware, long-lived installs</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p><strong>Inside the case,</strong> the <strong>motherboard</strong> is the nervous system: traces and chipsets route signals between CPU, RAM, expansion slots, storage buses, and onboard controllers. The <strong>CPU</strong> fetches and executes instructions; it is dumb without software, but nothing runs without it. <strong>RAM</strong> is the scratchpad—large enough to hold running apps and OS cache, and orders of magnitude faster than disk, which is why “add RAM” fixes some slowdowns (until you saturate something else). The <strong>GPU</strong> is optional on office PCs but essential for 3D, video editing, and modern composited UIs. The <strong>PSU</strong> must supply stable 12V/5V/3.3V rails sized for peak GPU+CPU load; under-spec PSUs cause mysterious reboots. <strong>Storage</strong> and the <strong>NIC</strong> (wired or Wi-Fi module) sit on buses (SATA, NVMe, PCIe, M.2). <strong>Cooling</strong> moves heat from dies to air; if airflow is blocked, the system throttles or shuts down to protect silicon.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Storage types &amp; memory behavior</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>HDDs</strong> store bits as magnetic patterns on spinning platters. A moving head seeks tracks—fast sequential reads, slower random small reads, vulnerable to shock. <strong>SSDs</strong> store charge in flash cells; no seek time, silent, great random I/O, but wear and cost per GB still matter at huge scale. <strong>NVMe</strong> puts flash on a <strong>PCIe</strong> lane with a protocol designed for SSDs (not the older SCSI mindset of SATA), so latency drops and queue depth scales—why NVMe “feels instant” for boot and app launch.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Volatile vs non-volatile</strong> is the power question: pull the plug on RAM and its contents are gone; SSD/HDD/ROM retain data. <strong>Local</strong> means you can point at the device; <strong>cloud</strong> means someone else’s data center, though sync tools keep local copies that blur the line for users.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Decision thinking:</strong> Bulk cold archive → cheap HDD. Everyday laptop → SSD/NVMe. Kiosk or embedded → small flash or eMMC. Exam questions often ask “which is fastest?” or “which is volatile?”—not “which brand?”\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Peripherals, printers, and drivers</h2>\r\n                        <p>Peripherals extend what the core PC can sense or act on. When you plug something in, the OS asks “what are you?” using identifiers exposed over USB or Bluetooth. <strong>Plug and Play</strong> automates IRQ/DMA/memory assignment compared to the bad old days, but the OS still needs a <strong>driver</strong>—a translator between generic OS calls and vendor-specific hardware.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Inkjets</strong> spray liquid ink; great for photos and mixed color, cartridges can dry out. <strong>Laser</strong> printers fuse powdered <strong>toner</strong> with heat; excellent for sharp text and office volume. <strong>Thermal</strong> printers use heat on special paper—receipts, shipping labels. Network printers get an IP; shared USB printers rely on a host PC or print server. If print jobs stall, the queue, driver, and connectivity layer are your three suspects.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Ports, video, and cables</h2>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Interface</th><th>Remember</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>USB-A</td><td>Classic rectangular; many legacy devices</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>USB-C</td><td>Reversible; may carry USB-only, DisplayPort Alt Mode, Thunderbolt, charging</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Thunderbolt 3/4</td><td>High bandwidth; daisy-chain; often same port shape as USB-C</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>HDMI / DisplayPort</td><td>Digital video to monitors/TVs; DP common on PCs, HDMI on TVs</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>RJ-45</td><td>Ethernet; wired LAN</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Audio 3.5 mm</td><td>TRS/TRRS headset/mic combos</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p><strong>Ethernet cabling:</strong> <strong>Cat5e</strong> handles 1 Gbps in typical office lengths. <strong>Cat6/6a</strong> improves crosstalk performance and supports 10 Gbps at shorter distances. <strong>Fiber</strong> uses light—immune to electrical noise, standard for long runs, ISP handoffs, and high-speed uplinks. Copper ends in <strong>RJ-45</strong>; fiber may use <strong>SFP</strong> modules.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Wireless: Bluetooth, NFC, Wi-Fi</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Bluetooth</strong> is a personal-area radio: low power, pairing, good for keyboards, audio, and short file swaps—not a replacement for building-wide LAN throughput. <strong>NFC</strong> is centimeters: tap-to-pay, tap-to-pair. <strong>Wi-Fi</strong> is your wireless LAN workhorse; it shares unlicensed spectrum with neighbors, microwaves, and Bluetooth, which is why placement, band choice, and channel width matter (Security chapter covers encryption).</p>\r\n                        <h2>Networking basics</h2>\r\n                        <p>Networks are layered. At the physical layer you have cables and radios; above that, devices speak <strong>Ethernet frames</strong> addressed by <strong>MAC</strong>. At layer 3, <strong>IP addresses</strong> let routers move packets across different subnets and across the world. Two machines on the same subnet talk locally (often via switch); to reach another network, traffic goes to a <strong>default gateway</strong>—usually your router’s LAN address.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Ports</strong> (like <code>443</code>) are not jacks on the wall; they are numbers in TCP/UDP headers telling the OS which application should receive the segment. That is how one public IP can host web, mail, and VPN—each service listens on its own port.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>LAN</strong> — Single site or logical grouping (home, office floor). <strong>WAN</strong> — Connects distant sites; the Internet is a public WAN. <strong>Router</strong> — Routes between subnets/networks; often includes NAT for home. <strong>Switch</strong> — Forwards frames inside a LAN by MAC. <strong>Modem</strong> — Terminates ISP link (cable/fiber/DSL). <strong>WAP</strong> — Adds Wi-Fi access to the wired LAN.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>DHCP</strong> saves you from typing IP, mask, gateway, and DNS by hand—essential when laptops roam. <strong>DNS</strong> is the phone book: humans remember <code>example.com</code>; stacks need numbers. If DNS breaks, “the Internet looks down” even when raw IP still works—a classic isolate-the-layer lesson.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Client-server</strong> centralizes services (files, authentication, databases). <strong>Peer-to-peer</strong> treats nodes as equals—simple shares, some updates, but harder to secure and audit at scale.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Mini scenario:</strong> PC gets 169.254.x.x APIPA address → likely no DHCP reachability (bad Wi-Fi, rogue switch, DHCP server down). PC gets correct IP but cannot browse → try ping gateway, then ping 8.8.8.8, then DNS—each step tells you which layer failed.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Internet access types &amp; Wi-Fi standards</h2>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Fiber</strong> — Glass, very high bandwidth, low latency; great for symmetric speeds.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cable</strong> — Shared neighborhood segment; fast downloads; upload varies.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>DSL</strong> — Copper phone lines; distance-sensitive.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cellular (LTE/5G)</strong> — Mobile broadband; hotspot tethering.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <p>Each Wi-Fi generation improved encoding, channel width, and multi-user tricks. <strong>802.11n</strong> brought better 2.4/5 GHz speeds; <strong>802.11ac</strong> pushed 5 GHz wave-2 gear; <strong>802.11ax</strong> (Wi-Fi 6) targets dense environments; <strong>Wi-Fi 6E</strong> adds <strong>6 GHz</strong> spectrum where regulators allow—more clean air, but shorter reach through walls. <strong>2.4 GHz</strong> is crowded (Bluetooth, microwaves, old gear) but travels farther; <strong>5 GHz</strong> offers more throughput with less range; <strong>6 GHz</strong> is premium spectrum for new laptops and phones.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Fiber vs cable vs DSL vs cellular</strong> is an economics and physics story: fiber offers huge symmetrical bandwidth and low latency when deployed; cable shares neighborhood coax; DSL degrades with copper length; cellular roams but faces towers and data caps.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Cloud &amp; virtualization</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Virtualization</strong> decouples operating systems from bare metal. A <strong>hypervisor</strong> schedules CPU time, carves RAM, and virtualizes disks and NICs so each guest OS believes it owns hardware. That enables <strong>snapshots</strong>, <strong>live migration</strong> in data centers, and “rent a VM by the hour.”</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Model</th><th>You manage</th><th>Vendor manages</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>IaaS</strong></td><td>OS, apps, data, some networking</td><td>Servers, storage, hypervisor, data center</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>PaaS</strong></td><td>App and data</td><td>Runtime, middleware, scaling, patching platform</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>SaaS</strong></td><td>Your content/config</td><td>Entire application stack</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p><strong>On-premises</strong> — You own the gear in your building. <strong>Public cloud</strong> — Shared provider (AWS/Azure/GCP style). <strong>Hybrid</strong> — Mix (e.g. AD on-prem + SaaS email). <strong>Hypervisor</strong> — Software/firmware that runs virtual machines: <strong>Type 1</strong> (bare-metal, ESXi/Hyper-V on server) vs <strong>Type 2</strong> (hosted on top of an OS, e.g. desktop VM apps).</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>IaaS</strong> is “give me VMs and disks”; you still patch the OS. <strong>PaaS</strong> is “give me a runtime and database service”; you focus on code. <strong>SaaS</strong> is “give me Gmail/Teams/365”—you configure, you do not compile the stack. The exam wants you to place a scenario into the right bucket: who patches the database engine? Who owns physical servers?</p>\r\n                        <h2>Basic maintenance &amp; support mindset</h2>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Preventive</strong> — Dust filters, cable strain relief, surge/UPS, scheduled backups, patch Tuesday cadence.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>ESD</strong> — Use anti-static strap/mat when handling boards; discharge before touching internals.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Environmental</strong> — Heat kills; ensure intake/exhaust clear; laptops on hard surfaces.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <h2>RAID concepts (recognition level)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>RAID</strong> combines multiple disks for speed, redundancy, or both—usually via a hardware controller or OS software RAID. Tech+ expects vocabulary, not calculator math.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Level</th><th>Idea</th><th>Trade-off</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>0</strong> (striping)</td><td>Data split across disks—fast reads/writes</td><td><strong>No redundancy</strong>; one disk dies → data loss</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>1</strong> (mirroring)</td><td>Two disks hold the same data</td><td>Survives one disk failure; costs 50% capacity</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>5</strong></td><td>Striping + distributed parity</td><td>Survives one disk failure; needs at least three disks</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>10</strong> (1+0)</td><td>Mirror of stripes</td><td>Performance + redundancy; needs at least four disks</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p>Exam distractors may offer “RAID 0 is safest”—false. “RAID 1 is for redundancy”—true. NAS appliances and servers advertise these modes in their GUIs.</p>\r\n                        <h2>IPv4 essentials for workstations</h2>\r\n                        <p>You do not subnet for Tech+, but you must recognize <strong>normal vs broken</strong> addresses. <strong>Private</strong> ranges (not routed on the public Internet): <code>10.0.0.0/8</code>, <code>172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255</code>, <code>192.168.0.0/16</code>. Home routers usually hand out <code>192.168.x.x</code>. <strong>APIPA</strong> <code>169.254.0.0/16</code> means “I could not get DHCP”—check cable, Wi-Fi, or DHCP server. <strong>Loopback</strong> <code>127.0.0.1</code> tests the local TCP/IP stack.</p>\r\n                        <p>A <strong>subnet mask</strong> (often <code>255.255.255.0</code> on small LANs) tells the host which bits identify the network vs the host. The <strong>default gateway</strong> is the router’s LAN IP on your subnet—traffic to other subnets goes there.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Well-known ports (memorize the hits)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Ports</strong> are application endpoints on top of IP. Firewalls filter by port; exams love “which service uses which port?”</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Port(s)</th><th>Protocol / service</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>20/21</td><td>FTP (data / control)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>22</td><td>SSH (secure shell)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>23</td><td>Telnet (insecure—avoid)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>25</td><td>SMTP (mail send)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>53</td><td>DNS</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>67/68</td><td>DHCP server / client</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>80</td><td>HTTP</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>110</td><td>POP3 (mail receive)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>143</td><td>IMAP (mail receive)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>443</td><td>HTTPS (HTTP over TLS)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>445</td><td>SMB / Windows file sharing</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>3389</td><td>RDP (Remote Desktop)</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <h2>Displays, resolution, and projectors</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Native resolution</strong> is the physical pixel grid of a panel—running “wrong” resolution looks soft or stretched. <strong>Aspect ratio</strong> (16:9 vs 16:10) matters for black bars. <strong>Refresh rate</strong> (Hz) is how often the image updates; higher feels smoother for motion. <strong>Mirroring</strong> shows the same image on laptop + projector; <strong>extended desktop</strong> gives a second workspace. If a conference room shows “no signal,” verify input source on the display, cable type (HDMI vs DP), and whether <strong>Win+P</strong> (or OS equivalent) is set to duplicate/extend.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Satellite, KVM, and docking</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Satellite Internet</strong> reaches rural areas with high latency (signal to orbit and back)—fine for email and streaming with buffer, poor for competitive online gaming. <strong>KVM</strong> (Keyboard, Video, Mouse) switches let one console control multiple PCs—common in server closets. A <strong>docking station</strong> or <strong>Thunderbolt hub</strong> expands a laptop to many monitors, Ethernet, and USB with one cable.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-recap\">\r\n                            <div class=\"lh-tg-recap-head\">Exam Essentials — hardware, devices, network, cloud</div>\r\n                            <h4>Ch.2 Peripherals &amp; connectors</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Throughput order (smallest→largest):</strong> bps, Kbps, Mbps, Gbps, Tbps. <strong>Uppercase B</strong> = bytes.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Video connectors to know:</strong> VGA, DVI, HDMI, DisplayPort, Thunderbolt, USB (video-capable).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Laser</strong> uses toner powder; <strong>inkjet</strong> uses liquid ink cartridges.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>External storage links:</strong> USB and Thunderbolt.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>UPS</strong> = battery backup on power loss; usually surge protection too.</li>\r\n                                <li>Modern <strong>keyboard/mouse</strong>: USB; legacy <strong>PS/2</strong>; very old mice: serial.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>RJ-45</strong> twisted-pair Ethernet; <strong>SFP</strong> on fiber; <strong>RJ-11</strong> phone line to modem.</li>\r\n                                <li>Make cables with a <strong>crimper</strong>; verify with a <strong>cable tester</strong>.</li>\r\n                                <li>Common device plugs: <strong>USB-A</strong>, <strong>USB-C</strong>, Thunderbolt, <strong>Lightning</strong> (Apple mobile).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Mirroring</strong> = same image on two displays; <strong>casting</strong> sends image to another screen while the source can do other work.</li>\r\n                                <li>Wireless: <strong>Wi-Fi</strong> primary LAN radio; mobile also uses <strong>Bluetooth</strong>, <strong>RF</strong>, <strong>NFC</strong>.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Install flow:</strong> connect → driver (or PnP) → configure (IP/web apps as needed).</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <h4>Ch.3 Devices &amp; IoT</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Servers</strong> provide services to others; <strong>workstations</strong> are daily-use systems.</li>\r\n                                <li>Mobile UX: tap, swipe, pinch, kinetic sensors; screen lock/orientation.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Tablet</strong> vs <strong>e-reader:</strong> tablets often larger, color; e-readers optimized for books, often grayscale.</li>\r\n                                <li>Connections in <strong>Settings</strong>: Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, sync, <strong>Airplane mode</strong> (kills cellular quickly).</li>\r\n                                <li>Apps: <strong>App Store</strong> (iOS) / <strong>Google Play</strong> (Android).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>AR</strong> overlays on real world; <strong>VR</strong> headset immersive world.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Consoles:</strong> games + often Internet + optical movie playback.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>IoT consumer:</strong> thermostats, security, appliances, entertainment, wearables, cars.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>IoT commercial:</strong> medical, manufacturing, transport, infrastructure.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <h4>Ch.8 Networking</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Network storage types:</strong> file server, <strong>NAS</strong>, cloud.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Internet access options:</strong> dial-up, DSL, cable, fiber, satellite, cellular, RF.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Wired</strong> = faster/more contained; <strong>wireless</strong> = mobility.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Modem</strong> (esp. legacy phone); <strong>switch</strong> LAN frames; <strong>AP</strong> Wi-Fi; <strong>router</strong> connects networks; <strong>firewall</strong> filters traffic.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Client/server</strong> vs <strong>peer-to-peer</strong>.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>LAN</strong> small area; <strong>WAN</strong> geographically spread.</li>\r\n                                <li>TCP/IP config: need <strong>IP + subnet mask</strong>; for Internet add <strong>default gateway</strong>.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>DHCP</strong> auto-assigns IP settings; <strong>DNS</strong> resolves names → IP.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>IP</strong> logical/changes; <strong>MAC</strong> physical NIC address; <strong>ports</strong> identify upper-layer protocol/service.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Wireless security best→worst:</strong> WPA3, WPA2, WPA, WEP.</li>\r\n                                <li>Services/protocols: <strong>HTTP/S</strong> web; <strong>FTP</strong> files; <strong>POP3/IMAP</strong> receive mail; <strong>SMTP</strong> send mail.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>802.11 a/b/g/n/ac/ax</strong> — ax newest; interference, distance, obstacles affect signal.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Wi-Fi bands:</strong> 2.4 GHz, 5 GHz, 6 GHz — higher band often more throughput, shorter range.</li>\r\n                                <li>SoHo Wi-Fi: change <strong>SSID</strong> &amp; defaults; know <strong>open</strong> vs <strong>WPA-class</strong> encryption.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <h4>Ch.9 Cloud &amp; AI</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Hypervisor</strong> shares host hardware among guest OSs; manages resources.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Guest OS</strong> only sees what the hypervisor assigns.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>IaaS</strong> = virtual hardware; <strong>PaaS</strong> adds dev tooling; <strong>SaaS</strong> = apps too (e.g. M365, Google Docs).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Cloud deployment:</strong> on-prem, public Internet cloud, hybrid.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Chatbots:</strong> customer service, scripted flows, escalate to humans.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Assistants:</strong> Alexa/Siri/Google — broad tasks.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Generative AI:</strong> generated code vs generated content (text/graphics).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Predictive:</strong> autocorrect, query suggestions, shopping recommendations.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <p class=\"src\">Topic recap for connectors, devices, networking, and cloud models.</p>\r\n                        </div></div>","tech-03":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><div class=\"lh-tg-summary\">\r\n                            <h3>Chapter snapshot</h3>\r\n                            <p>Explain how an <strong>OS</strong> orchestrates hardware and apps, when to use <strong>GUI vs CLI</strong>, categories of software you deploy daily, <strong>browser</strong> controls that affect privacy and malware risk, and how <strong>AI tools</strong> differ (chat, assistants, generative, predictive).</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>Software chapters on the exam are less about memorizing every menu path and more about <strong>concepts</strong>: where software comes from, how it is licensed, how browsers expose you to the open web, and how AI tools differ in risk and use case.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Operating systems — purpose and types</h2>\r\n                        <p>An operating system is not “just another app.” It is the <strong>trusted layer</strong> between hardware and programs: it decides which process runs on which core, how RAM is shared, who may read a file, and how bytes move to disk or across the NIC. Without an OS, every program would need its own drivers for every printer and GPU—impossible to maintain.</p>\r\n                        <p>The <strong>kernel</strong> stays resident and privileged; user applications call into it for sensitive work (open file, allocate memory, send packet). The <strong>file system</strong> adds names, folders, permissions, and metadata (created date, size). The <strong>shell</strong> is your interface: a <strong>GUI</strong> renders windows and touch targets; a <strong>CLI</strong> accepts text commands and scripts—critical for repeatability and remote admin.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>OS category</th><th>Examples / ideas</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Desktop</td><td>Windows, macOS, Linux distributions for PCs</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Mobile</td><td>iOS, Android — app sandboxing, touch-first</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Server</td><td>Windows Server, Linux server — remote admin, services, uptime</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Embedded</td><td>Firmware on printers, TVs, cars — fixed function, long lifecycle</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-key\">\r\n                            <strong>Why CLI matters on exams:</strong> Scripting, remote repair, and repeatable fixes. The GUI hides steps; the CLI shows exact commands for logs and automation.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Application architecture (how software is delivered)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Where code executes changes updates, offline use, and security boundaries. A <strong>thick</strong> client installs binaries locally—fast UI, works offline (often), but patching is your responsibility. A <strong>web app</strong> ships logic from a server each visit; thin local footprint, but you need connectivity (or progressive offline tricks) and you trust the browser sandbox. A <strong>thin client / VDI / DaaS</strong> model streams pixels or remotes a session: the data often never lands on the endpoint, which helps loss/theft scenarios but demands a solid network.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Local / “thick” client</strong> — Installed on disk; runs mostly on local CPU/RAM (office suites, games).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Web app</strong> — Runs in the browser; UI in HTML/JS; data often on remote servers.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Thin client / streaming</strong> — Little local processing; displays remote desktop or hosted session (<strong>DaaS</strong> fits here).</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <h2>Software types you must recognize</h2>\r\n                        <p>Classification questions are not trivia—they mirror how IT buys and supports software. <strong>Productivity</strong> suites create artifacts (docs, slides, sheets). <strong>Collaboration</strong> tools coordinate people across time zones (mail, chat, meetings, shared files). <strong>Browsers</strong> are universal clients for HTTP/S and many internal portals. <strong>Remote support</strong> tools are powerful: treat them like surgical instruments—use only with consent, logging, and policy.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Productivity</strong> — Word processor, spreadsheet, presentation, PDF tools, note-taking.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Collaboration</strong> — Email client, chat (Teams/Slack-style), video conferencing, shared drives, calendars.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Browsers</strong> — Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari; render <code>HTML</code>; enforce same-origin policies with caveats (extensions).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Remote support</strong> — Screen sharing, remote control, unattended access — only with explicit permission and policy; logs sessions for audit.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <p><strong>Installation sources:</strong> Official vendor site, Microsoft Store / platform store, enterprise <strong>MDM</strong> push, or packaged <strong>MSI/EXE</strong>. Avoid bundled installers from random download portals.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Updates, licensing, and hygiene</h2>\r\n                        <p>Updates are not “annoying reboots”—they ship <strong>security patches</strong> for bugs attackers already study. Deferring them increases risk. Licensing tells you <em>how many installs</em>, <em>whether VMs are allowed</em>, and <em>who you can call for support</em>. <strong>OEM</strong> licenses ride with a machine; <strong>retail/volume</strong> licenses transfer differently. <strong>Open source</strong> is not automatically “no rules”—it has licenses too (GPL vs MIT differ in obligations). Pirated keys and cracked installers are a malware distribution channel and a compliance failure.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Web browser configuration (high-yield for Tech+)</h2>\r\n                        <p>The browser is the user’s most attacked daily app: it fetches untrusted code (JavaScript), renders it, and often stores credentials. Configuration is defense in depth: reduce attack surface (extensions), limit tracking (cookies, third parties), and keep secrets out of easy Autofill on shared PCs.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Private / InPrivate / Incognito</strong> — Reduces <em>local</em> history/cookies for that window; does <strong>not</strong> hide traffic from employer, ISP, or websites.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Extensions</strong> — Can read page content; remove unused ones; prefer official stores; review permissions.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cache</strong> — Stores images/scripts for speed; clearing fixes stale pages and some login glitches.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cookies</strong> — Session/state; third-party cookies used for tracking — know they differ from cache.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Pop-up blockers</strong> — Stop malicious or annoying windows; may need exceptions for legitimate apps.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Bookmarks / favorites</strong> — Organize; avoid typosquatting URLs.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Password manager</strong> — Browser built-in or dedicated app; generates/stores unique passwords; resists phishing by filling only matching domains.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Troubleshooting tie-in:</strong> “Website loads broken after update” → hard refresh or clear cache. “Can’t log in after policy change” → cookies/session for that site.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>AI basics (categories, risks, responsible use)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Modern AI on the exam is conceptual, not “train your own model.” Understand <em>what each tool is for</em> and <em>what can go wrong</em>. <strong>Chatbots</strong> and <strong>assistants</strong> feel similar; chatbots are often narrow (support flows), assistants broad (device control). <strong>Generative</strong> systems invent plausible text/media—useful drafts, dangerous facts. <strong>Predictive</strong> systems score likelihood: spam, fraud, “you might also buy…” They need training data; feeding them customer <strong>PII</strong> without policy is a privacy incident.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Chatbots</strong> — Scripted/narrow dialog; escalate to humans; verify facts.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Assistants</strong> — Cross-app actions; check default listening/sharing settings.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Generative AI</strong> — Text, images, code; verify licenses and correctness before ship.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Predictive AI / ML</strong> — Ranking, filtering, suggestions; data governance matters.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-note\">\r\n                            <strong>Work policy:</strong> Many employers restrict which AI services may receive customer data. When in doubt, use approved tools only.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Windows tools that show up in real support (and exams)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Task Manager</strong> (<code>Ctrl+Shift+Esc</code>): <strong>Processes</strong> shows CPU/RAM hogs; <strong>Performance</strong> graphs disk, network, and GPU; <strong>Startup</strong> disables boot-time apps; <strong>Users</strong> shows who is logged on. Ending a frozen app is safer than rebooting the whole PC when only one process misbehaves.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Settings</strong> (gear icon) is the modern control center for display, sound, network, accounts, and Windows Update. <strong>Control Panel</strong> still exists for legacy applets (Programs and Features, power plans). <strong>Device Manager</strong> lists hardware with driver status—a yellow warning icon means a driver problem. <strong>Disk Cleanup</strong> / Storage sense reclaims space; <strong>Event Viewer</strong> logs system, security, and application errors for deeper troubleshooting.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>File Explorer</strong> + <strong>Recycle Bin</strong>: deleted files may be recoverable until the bin is emptied or space is overwritten. <strong>Safe Mode</strong> boots with minimal drivers—useful when a bad driver or startup program prevents normal login.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Common file extensions (know the category)</h2>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Extension</th><th>Typical meaning</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.exe</code>, <code>.msi</code></td><td>Windows installer / executable</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.bat</code>, <code>.cmd</code></td><td>Batch scripts (can run arbitrary commands—treat like executables)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.ps1</code></td><td>PowerShell script</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.dll</code></td><td>Dynamic link library (shared code, not double-clicked)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.pdf</code></td><td>Portable Document Format</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.zip</code>, <code>.7z</code></td><td>Compressed archives (scan before extract—malware hides inside)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.docx</code>, <code>.xlsx</code>, <code>.pptx</code></td><td>Office Open XML documents</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.jpg</code>, <code>.png</code>, <code>.gif</code></td><td>Raster images</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.mp4</code>, <code>.mov</code></td><td>Video containers</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><code>.html</code>, <code>.htm</code></td><td>Web markup (opened in browsers)</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <h2>Chrome OS, Linux, and “where did my programs go?”</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Chrome OS</strong> centers the browser and Android/Linux containers—great for schools and kiosks; local storage is limited; updates are fast. Mainstream <strong>Linux</strong> distributions (Ubuntu, Fedora, etc.) share the same conceptual pieces as Windows (kernel, package manager, permissions) but use different installers (<code>.deb</code>, <code>.rpm</code>, repos) and often a <strong>terminal</strong> for admin tasks. macOS is Unix under the hood with a different GUI and Gatekeeper signing model—exams may mention “vendor store” vs sideloading.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>MDM</strong> (mobile device management) pushes policies, apps, and wipes to corporate phones—know it as the enterprise control plane for mobile OSes.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-recap\">\r\n                            <div class=\"lh-tg-recap-head\">Exam Essentials — operating systems &amp; applications</div>\r\n                            <h4>Operating system (Ch.4)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li>OS components: <strong>file system</strong> traits, file management, built-in apps/utilities, <strong>services</strong>, <strong>processes</strong>, <strong>drivers</strong>, user interfaces.</li>\r\n                                <li>File system features: <strong>compression</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, types &amp; <strong>extensions</strong>.</li>\r\n                                <li>File management: folders/directories, <strong>permissions</strong>, naming rules.</li>\r\n                                <li>OS categories: <strong>workstation, server, mobile, embedded</strong>; know families (Windows, Linux, macOS, Chrome OS, iOS, Android).</li>\r\n                                <li>Management areas: users, access control, apps, processes, services, devices, disk space, memory; navigating structure, metadata, running programs.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <h4>Software &amp; browsers (Ch.5)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Executable extensions (know these):</strong> <code>.exe</code>, <code>.msi</code>, <code>.app</code>, <code>.bat</code>, and similar vendor launchers (some environments also use helper-style executables).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Productivity:</strong> word processing, spreadsheets, presentations, diagramming, browsers.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Collaboration:</strong> email clients, conferencing, online workspace, document storage/sharing.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Utilities:</strong> anti-malware, software firewalls, IM, remote support, compression, PDF readers.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Licensing:</strong> EULA limits users/seats; <strong>activation</strong> may bind software to a machine.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Open source</strong> vs <strong>proprietary</strong>; <strong>subscription</strong> vs one-time/perpetual purchase.</li>\r\n                                <li>Get software from <strong>OEM/vendor</strong> sites vs third-party download portals—verify legitimacy.</li>\r\n                                <li>Install: run installer / autorun media; uninstall via OS software manager.</li>\r\n                                <li>Browser: update version; manage add-ons/extensions; profile sync; bookmarks; default search; clear <strong>cache</strong>; pop-up blocking; <strong>private browsing</strong>; password tools.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <p class=\"src\">Topic recap for OS concepts, software types, browsers, and licensing.</p>\r\n                        </div><h2>Programming &amp; data representation (study guide Ch.4)</h2><div class=\"lh-tg-summary\">\r\n                            <h3>Chapter snapshot</h3>\r\n                            <p>Tech+ does not make you a developer—it checks that you can compare <strong>how languages run</strong>, name common <strong>data types</strong>, follow <strong>variables → structures → logic</strong>, and read simple <strong>pseudocode</strong> and <strong>flowcharts</strong>.</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>You are learning to read the <em>shape</em> of programs: how data is named, grouped, repeated, and decided. That is enough to discuss software with developers, to follow basic scripts, and to answer “what kind of language is this?” on the exam.</p>\r\n                        <h2>How programs run: interpreted vs compiled vs query</h2>\r\n                        <p>Source code is human-readable; processors execute numeric instructions. A <strong>compiler</strong> bridges that gap ahead of time: it analyzes the whole program (syntax, types), emits machine code or bytecode, and may optimize. You get faster startup at run time and errors caught before deployment—but you must rebuild when code changes.</p>\r\n                        <p>An <strong>interpreter</strong> (or runtime) reads the program as it runs, which makes iteration fast and deployment simple (“just copy the script”). Hybrid systems (Java on the JVM, Python with caches) blend both worlds. Neither is “better”—they fit different domains.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>SQL</strong> is declarative: you describe <em>what set of rows</em> you want; the database engine decides <em>how</em> to scan indexes and join tables. That is why SQL sits in its own column below—it talks to data, not directly to the CPU instruction stream like C.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Category</th><th>Idea</th><th>Examples (illustrative)</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Compiled</strong></td><td>Source translated to machine code <em>before</em> run; often catches errors at build time</td><td>C, C++, Rust, Go (AOT style)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Interpreted / hybrid</strong></td><td>Source or bytecode executed by runtime; flexible, portable; may use JIT</td><td>Python, JavaScript, Java on JVM</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Query language</strong></td><td>Declares <em>what</em> data you want from a database</td><td>SQL (<code>SELECT</code>, <code>INSERT</code>, <code>UPDATE</code>, <code>DELETE</code>)</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p>An <strong>IDE</strong> bundles editor, debugger, build tools, and sometimes visual designers—faster than Notepad for real projects.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Data types (primitive concepts)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Types tell the language how to store bits and which operations are legal. Adding two integers is arithmetic; adding two strings might mean concatenation—same plus sign, different meaning. <strong>Floats</strong> approximate real numbers and can surprise you with rounding (money apps often use integers of cents). <strong>Booleans</strong> drive every decision point.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>String</strong> — Sequence of characters; <code>\"hello\"</code>.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Integer</strong> — Whole numbers; <code>-3, 0, 42</code>.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Float / double</strong> — Numbers with fractional parts; scientific and currency math (watch rounding).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Boolean</strong> — <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>; drives conditions.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <h2>Structures: variables through objects</h2>\r\n                        <p>Small programs can live in one file; real systems organize logic. A <strong>variable</strong> is a named box; a <strong>constant</strong> is a box you promise not to repack—useful for configuration like tax rates. An <strong>array</strong> lines up many values by index—great for loops. A <strong>function</strong> hides a recipe: parameters in, return value out, reusable everywhere.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Object-oriented</strong> thinking models nouns in the problem domain: a “customer” has properties (name, balance) and methods (placeOrder, resetPassword). The <strong>class</strong> is the cookie cutter; an <strong>object</strong> is one cookie. Tech+ will not make you code a full class, but it <em>will</em> ask whether a snippet behaves like data+behavior.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Variable</strong> — Named storage whose value can change (depending on language rules).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Constant</strong> — Value fixed after assignment; prevents accidental overwrite.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Array / list</strong> — Ordered collection accessed by index; same type or mixed depending on language.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Function / method</strong> — Named block with parameters and return value; reduces duplication.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Object</strong> — Combines <strong>properties</strong> (data) and <strong>methods</strong> (behavior); foundation of OOP.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <h2>Logic: branching and looping</h2>\r\n                        <p>Programs are mostly <strong>sequence</strong>, <strong>selection</strong>, and <strong>repetition</strong>. Branching answers “under what condition do we take path B?” Loops answer “how many times?” or “until what becomes false?” Exam pseudocode may nest loops inside branches—trace carefully, writing down variable values on paper if needed.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Branching</strong> — <code>if / else if / else</code>, <code>switch</code> on discrete values, short-circuit evaluation. <strong>Loops</strong> — <code>for</code> (known iterations), <code>while</code> (condition-driven), <code>foreach</code> over collections. Watch <strong>off-by-one</strong> errors and infinite loops.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Pseudocode &amp; flowcharts</h2>\r\n                        <p>Teams sketch before they code. <strong>Pseudocode</strong> is a structured English-ish outline—indentation shows nesting; it reads like code but ignores strict syntax, so focus on sequence, conditions, and loops. <strong>Flowcharts</strong> are graphical; the exam cares that you follow arrows through decisions without skipping a branch. Neither format runs on a CPU; both exist to communicate intent and catch logic errors cheaply.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Sample pseudocode — print even numbers 2–10:</strong><br>\r\n                            <code>FOR n FROM 2 TO 10 STEP 2</code><br>\r\n                            <code>&nbsp;&nbsp;PRINT n</code><br>\r\n                            <code>END FOR</code>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Flowchart symbol (typical)</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Rounded rectangle</td><td>Start / End</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Rectangle</td><td>Process step</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Diamond</td><td>Decision (yes/no branch)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Parallelogram</td><td>Input / Output</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-key\">\r\n                            <strong>Exam skill:</strong> Trace the diagram top-to-bottom; at each diamond follow the correct branch for the given input values.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Markup vs programming vs assembly</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>HTML</strong> and <strong>XML</strong> are <strong>markup</strong> languages—they describe structure (headings, paragraphs, tags), not full algorithms. Browsers render HTML; parsers validate XML schemas. Do not call HTML a “compiled programming language.”</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Scripting</strong> languages (<strong>JavaScript</strong> in browsers, <strong>Python</strong> for automation, <strong>PHP</strong> on servers) are often interpreted or JIT-compiled—flexible for glue code and web.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Assembly</strong> is a low-level mnemonic view of machine instructions—tied to a CPU architecture. Compilers may emit assembly as an intermediate step; humans use it for drivers, bootloaders, and extreme optimization, not daily app dev on Tech+.</p>\r\n                        <h2>ASCII, Unicode, and “why emoji work”</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>ASCII</strong> maps English letters, digits, and punctuation to 7-bit codes (128 characters)—fine for legacy English text. <strong>Unicode</strong> is a universal character set that includes accented letters, scripts worldwide, symbols, and emoji. <strong>UTF-8</strong> encodes Unicode in bytes and stays compact for English while scaling to international text. Exam angle: Unicode is a <em>superset</em> of ASCII for practical purposes.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Second trace: nested branch + loop</h2>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Pseudocode — print “OK” for scores ≥70, else “Retry,” but skip negatives:</strong><br>\r\n                            <code>FOR EACH score IN list</code><br>\r\n                            <code>&nbsp;&nbsp;IF score &lt; 0 THEN SKIP</code><br>\r\n                            <code>&nbsp;&nbsp;ELSE IF score &gt;= 70 THEN PRINT \"OK\"</code><br>\r\n                            <code>&nbsp;&nbsp;ELSE PRINT \"Retry\"</code><br>\r\n                            <code>END FOR</code><br>\r\n                            Trace with <code>[85, -5, 60]</code>: prints OK, (nothing for -5), Retry.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p><strong>Version control</strong> (e.g., Git) tracks changes to source over time—rollback, branches, collaboration. You may see it as “where developers store code history,” not something you configure on Tech+.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-recap\">\r\n                            <div class=\"lh-tg-recap-head\">Exam Essentials — software development basics</div>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Notations:</strong> binary, decimal, octal, hex; character sets <strong>ASCII</strong> and <strong>Unicode</strong> (Unicode superset of ASCII).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Data types:</strong> char, string, integer, float, Boolean.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Compiled</strong> languages: compiler runs once → run many times. <strong>Interpreted:</strong> interpreted each run (no separate compile step like compiled languages).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Markup</strong> examples: HTML, XML. <strong>Scripting</strong> examples: JavaScript, VBScript, Python, PHP, Perl.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Query languages</strong> retrieve/insert DB data (mostly retrieve).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Assembly</strong> for lowest-level / hardware access.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Pseudocode</strong> annotates logic for humans; <strong>flowcharts</strong> plan/organize program structure.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Branching:</strong> if/then/else. <strong>Looping:</strong> while (book emphasis).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Constants</strong> fixed; <strong>variables</strong> change.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Arrays</strong> fixed length, same type; <strong>vectors</strong> dynamic, can mix types (per book).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Functions/methods</strong> group tasks; <strong>objects</strong> bundle attributes/properties and methods—built from <strong>classes</strong> (blueprint).</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <p class=\"src\">Topic recap for languages, types, logic, and design notations.</p>\r\n                        </div></div>","tech-04":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><div class=\"lh-tg-summary\">\r\n                            <h3>Chapter snapshot</h3>\r\n                            <p>Explain why organizations hoard data responsibly, how <strong>analytics</strong> and <strong>big data</strong> differ in scale, what a <strong>database</strong> stores, relational vs non-relational trade-offs, and how <strong>backups</strong> protect against mistakes and ransomware.</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>Data topics tie directly to real job stories: reporting, compliance, restores after someone deletes the wrong folder, and choosing structured tables versus flexible document stores.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Why data is valuable</h2>\r\n                        <p>Organizations do not collect data for sport—they expect <strong>better decisions, automation, or revenue</strong>. A retailer studies baskets to stock shelves; a school studies grades to target tutoring; a factory studies sensor streams to predict maintenance. When data is wrong, incomplete, or biased, models and dashboards lie confidently. That is <strong>garbage in, garbage out</strong>. Regulations exist because personal data can harm people if leaked or misused: <strong>GDPR</strong> in the EU, sector rules like HIPAA-style protections for health data, and state privacy laws in the US.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Analytics, big data, and data-driven decisions</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Analytics</strong> is the everyday work of SQL queries, spreadsheets, and BI dashboards—datasets that still fit mostly in one place. <strong>Big data</strong> is the regime where volume, speed, or variety forces distributed systems: think clickstreams, genomics, or city-wide IoT. You do not need to engineer Hadoop for Tech+; you need to recognize <em>why</em> classic relational databases strain at that scale. <strong>Data-driven</strong> culture means leadership asks for evidence—but evidence is only as good as governance and definitions.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Analytics</strong> — Dashboards, reports, statistics on datasets you can reasonably move into one tool.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Big data</strong> — Often described with <strong>volume, velocity, variety</strong>; needs distributed storage and processing (Hadoop/Spark-style ecosystem at a high level).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Data-driven decision</strong> — Leadership chooses actions supported by metrics, not only gut feel.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <h2>Database fundamentals</h2>\r\n                        <p>A <strong>flat file</strong> (one giant spreadsheet or CSV) works until two people edit at once, until you need enforced rules (“order total must match line items”), or until you need fast lookups on millions of rows. A <strong>database</strong> adds a <strong>DBMS</strong> engine that handles concurrency, crash recovery, indexing, and permissions.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Relational</strong> model — Data in <strong>tables</strong> (relations). Each <strong>row</strong> is a record; each <strong>column</strong> is a field with a type. A <strong>primary key</strong> uniquely identifies a row. A <strong>foreign key</strong> references a primary key in another table, enforcing relationships (customer → orders).</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Non-relational (NoSQL)</strong> — Document stores (JSON documents), key-value caches, wide-column, graph DBs—chosen when schema flexibility or massive scale matters.</p>\r\n                        <p>Think of <strong>schema</strong> as a contract: column names, types, and rules. Changing schema without planning breaks apps. <strong>CRUD</strong> maps to SQL verbs you should recognize: create rows (<code>INSERT</code>), read (<code>SELECT</code>), update (<code>UPDATE</code>), delete (<code>DELETE</code>). Structure changes use <code>CREATE/ALTER/DROP</code> on tables.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>SQL pattern (recognition only):</strong> <code>SELECT name, email FROM customers WHERE state = 'TX';</code> — retrieves columns from a table with a filter.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>Common app actions acronym <strong>CRUD</strong>: <strong>C</strong>reate, <strong>R</strong>ead, <strong>U</strong>pdate, <strong>D</strong>elete.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Backups: scope and location</h2>\r\n                        <p>Backups are an insurance policy—useless if you never test a restore. <strong>Ransomware</strong> made offline or immutable copies famous: if your only backup is a mapped drive letter, malware encrypts it too. <strong>File-level</strong> backup protects Sally’s Documents; <strong>image backup</strong> captures OS + apps so you can rebuild a machine after disk death without two days of reinstalling.</p>\r\n                        <p>Local copies are fast to restore; off-site/cloud copies survive building loss. Rotate media, encrypt sensitive archives, and document <em>who</em> is allowed to run restores (least privilege applies to backup consoles too).</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>File / folder backup</strong> — User documents, photos, databases export—fast restore of data but not full OS state.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>System / image backup</strong> — Snapshot of OS, apps, drivers—bare-metal or full machine restore.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Local</strong> — External drive, NAS on LAN; quick restores.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cloud / off-site</strong> — Survives fire/theft; watch encryption and retention policies.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-key\">\r\n                            <strong>3-2-1 rule (classic):</strong> At least <strong>three</strong> copies, on <strong>two</strong> different media, with <strong>one</strong> off-site. Test a restore before you need it.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Full vs incremental vs differential backups</h2>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Type</th><th>What is copied</th><th>Restore complexity</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Full</strong></td><td>Everything selected (whole system or dataset)</td><td>Easiest—restore one full set</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Incremental</strong></td><td>Only files changed since the <em>last backup of any kind</em></td><td>May need full + every incremental in order</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Differential</strong></td><td>Changes since the <em>last full</em></td><td>Restore full + latest differential</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p>Cloud sync (OneDrive/Google Drive) is <strong>not</strong> a full image backup—it may not recover OS state, and ransomware can encrypt synced copies if versioning is weak.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Normalization (one-sentence version)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Normalization</strong> splits redundant data into related tables so you update a fact in one place (e.g., customer address lives in <code>customers</code>, not repeated on every order row). Over-normalization can mean many joins for simple reports—<strong>denormalized</strong> star schemas appear in analytics warehouses for speed.</p>\r\n                        <h2>ETL, warehouses, and BI (vocabulary)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>ETL</strong> (Extract, Transform, Load) pulls data from sources, cleans/conforms it, and loads it into a warehouse. A <strong>data warehouse</strong> is a central store optimized for reporting across systems. <strong>Business intelligence (BI)</strong> tools build dashboards from that data. Tech+ may contrast “operational OLTP database” (many small fast transactions) with “analytical” workloads (big scans, aggregates).</p>\r\n                        <h2>More SQL patterns (recognition)</h2>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Filter + sort:</strong> <code>SELECT product, price FROM inventory WHERE price &lt; 100 ORDER BY price DESC;</code><br>\r\n                            <strong>Join (combine tables):</strong> <code>SELECT orders.id, customers.name FROM orders JOIN customers ON orders.customer_id = customers.id;</code> — links rows where foreign key matches primary key.<br>\r\n                            <strong>Insert / update / delete:</strong> <code>INSERT INTO</code> adds rows; <code>UPDATE</code> changes existing rows (always use a <code>WHERE</code> or you update everything); <code>DELETE</code> removes rows (same <code>WHERE</code> warning).\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>A <strong>database dump</strong> is often a logical export (SQL statements or portable format)—restoring may require an empty database first. A <strong>bare-metal</strong> or image backup captures the whole machine state.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-recap\">\r\n                            <div class=\"lh-tg-recap-head\">Exam Essentials — databases &amp; data continuity</div>\r\n                            <h4>Database fundamentals (Ch.7)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li>Databases <strong>manage</strong> data: create, import/input, query, report.</li>\r\n                                <li>Prefer a DB over flat files when you need <strong>concurrent users</strong>, large/varied data, speed, scale, persistence, availability, security.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Structured</strong> data in rows/columns—predictable, easy to query.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Unstructured</strong> mixed types (email, docs, images…); <strong>semistructured</strong> = unstructured + metadata tags.</li>\r\n                                <li>Relational: <strong>schema</strong>, tables, rows, columns, constraints.</li>\r\n                                <li>Exactly one <strong>primary key</strong> per table (unique row, no nulls); multiple <strong>foreign keys</strong> allowed.</li>\r\n                                <li>Nonrelational types called out: <strong>document</strong> DBs and <strong>key-value</strong> DBs.</li>\r\n                                <li>Access styles: direct, manual, programmatic, UI, utilities, query/report builders.</li>\r\n                                <li>DDL flavor: <strong>CREATE / ALTER / DROP</strong> for structures; DML: <strong>SELECT, INSERT, DELETE, UPDATE</strong> for data.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Database dump</strong> vs full <strong>backup</strong> restore paths differ—know dumps may need a fresh empty DB first.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <h4>Data continuity &amp; backups (Ch.12)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Fault tolerance:</strong> plan for failure; use replication, redundancy, backups for data/network/power.</li>\r\n                                <li>Backups often track changed files (e.g. <strong>archive bit</strong> concept in book).</li>\r\n                                <li>Define <strong>backup type</strong>, <strong>location</strong> (local, server, cloud), <strong>schedule</strong>—then <strong>test restores</strong>.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>DRP</strong> (disaster recovery) prioritizes what comes back first.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <p class=\"src\">Topic recap for relational/non-relational data and backup continuity.</p>\r\n                        </div></div>","tech-05":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><div class=\"lh-tg-summary\">\r\n                            <h3>Chapter snapshot</h3>\r\n                            <p>Map incidents to <strong>CIA</strong>, separate <strong>authentication vs authorization</strong>, recognize <strong>human and technical attacks</strong>, harden endpoints, handle <strong>passwords and encryption</strong> sensibly, and lock down <strong>Wi-Fi</strong>.</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <p>Security on this exam is practical end-user and small-office level: recognize threats, apply sane defaults, and explain <em>why</em> a control exists—not exploit development or enterprise SOC playbooks.</p>\r\n                        <h2>CIA triad and access control</h2>\r\n                        <p>Security goals compete with convenience and cost. The <strong>CIA triad</strong> is the shorthand examiners use to sort controls. <strong>Confidentiality</strong> asks: “Could someone who should not see this still see it?” Encryption, file permissions, and training reduce leaks. <strong>Integrity</strong> asks: “Was this altered in transit or on disk without us knowing?” Signed updates, hashes, and access logs support integrity. <strong>Availability</strong> asks: “Can legitimate users reach the service when they need it?” Redundant power, backups, and DDoS defenses protect availability—an attacker who cannot steal data may still try to knock you offline.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Confidentiality</strong> — Only authorized users/systems read secrets (encryption, permissions, clean desk).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Integrity</strong> — Data and configs are accurate and unmodified (hashing, patching tampering, change control).</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Availability</strong> — Services stay up (redundancy, backups, DDoS mitigation, UPS).</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <p><strong>Authentication</strong> answers “who are you?” <strong>Authorization</strong> answers “what may you do?” A receptionist might authenticate to the network but not be <em>authorized</em> to open payroll. <strong>Least privilege</strong> limits blast radius when credentials leak. <strong>MFA</strong> adds a second factor—something you have (token) or are (biometric)—so stolen passwords are not enough.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Threats: phishing, social engineering, malware</h2>\r\n                        <p>Many breaches start with a person, not a missing patch. <strong>Phishing</strong> clones trusted brands, invents urgency (“invoice overdue”), and links to fake login pages. <strong>Spear phishing</strong> uses your name and context. <strong>Vishing</strong> and <strong>smishing</strong> move the same tricks to phone and SMS. The defense is skepticism + verification: call the company on a known number, don’t use the one in the suspicious message.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Social engineering</strong> exploits helpful instincts: tailgating through a door, USB drives labeled “Payroll” left in a parking lot, fake IT calls. Policy + awareness + physical controls beat pure technology here.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Malware type</th><th>High-level behavior</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Virus</td><td>Attaches to files; needs user action often</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Worm</td><td>Self-spreads across network</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Trojan</td><td>Disguised as legitimate software</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Ransomware</td><td>Encrypts data; demands payment—backups are the recovery story</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Spyware / keylogger</td><td>Steals keystrokes or monitors activity</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>Rootkit</td><td>Hides deep in OS; tough to remove</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Story thread:</strong> User opens a “shipping notice” attachment → macro runs → <strong>trojan</strong> drops <strong>spyware</strong> → credentials exfiltrated → attacker uses <strong>ransomware</strong> weeks later. Good backups and least-privilege accounts limit damage; layered defenses catch different stages.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Device hardening</h2>\r\n                        <p>Hardening is subtraction: remove what you do not need, patch what you keep, and monitor the rest. Unused services are latent vulnerabilities. <strong>AutoPlay</strong> launching USB content is an easy policy win. Host <strong>firewalls</strong> block unexpected inbound; <strong>anti-malware</strong> adds signature and behavior checks. Full-disk encryption protects confidentiality if a laptop is stolen—not availability if the thief formats the drive, but your data does not walk away readable.</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Patching</strong> — OS, firmware, apps; prioritize critical CVEs.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Anti-malware / EDR</strong> — Real-time scanning, behavioral detection.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Firewall</strong> — Host firewall blocks unexpected inbound; network firewall segments LAN from WAN.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Disable unused services / ports</strong> — Shrinks attack surface.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Encryption at rest</strong> — BitLocker/FileVault/device encryption for lost hardware.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <h2>Safe software practices</h2>\r\n                        <p>Honor <strong>licenses</strong> and <strong>EULA</strong> (seat count, virtualization rights). Download only from <strong>vendor or first-party stores</strong>; verify checksums when provided. <strong>Piracy</strong> risks fines, malware, and no support.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Passwords and encryption in transit</h2>\r\n                        <p>Humans reuse passwords because memory is limited—attackers exploit that with <strong>credential stuffing</strong> (try leaked email/password pairs everywhere). Unique passwords per site contain the blast radius. A <strong>password manager</strong> generates entropy-heavy secrets and resists phishing by filling only matching domains.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Data at rest</strong> sits on disk or flash; steal the device, you have the bits—unless encryption makes them ciphertext. <strong>Data in transit</strong> crosses Wi-Fi, ISP links, and data centers—any hop can be observed on hostile networks. <strong>HTTPS</strong> wraps HTTP in TLS: the browser validates the server certificate chain before exchanging keys. A VPN adds another encrypted tunnel—valuable on untrusted Wi-Fi or for remote access to a corporate LAN— but you still must trust the VPN operator and keep endpoints patched.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-note\">\r\n                            <strong>SSL/TLS note:</strong> <code>SSL</code> is legacy naming; modern sites use <strong>TLS</strong>. Exams may still say SSL colloquially.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Wireless security checklist</h2>\r\n                        <p>Home and small-office routers are full computers with default passwords printed on stickers—bots scan for them constantly. <strong>WPA2/WPA3</strong> with a strong passphrase beats “open” Wi-Fi for confidentiality of wireless frames. <strong>Guest networks</strong> isolate visitors from file shares and printers. Firmware updates close remote-management bugs; disabling unused features (WPS where flawed, cloud admin if not needed) shrinks attack surface.</p>\r\n                        <ol>\r\n                            <li>Change default <strong>router admin</strong> password and disable remote admin unless required.</li>\r\n                            <li>Set a non-default <strong>SSID</strong> (hiding SSID is not real security).</li>\r\n                            <li>Use <strong>WPA3</strong> (or WPA2-AES); never <strong>WEP</strong> or open networks for sensitive work.</li>\r\n                            <li>Enable <strong>guest network</strong> for visitors; isolate from LAN.</li>\r\n                            <li>Update router <strong>firmware</strong>; disable WPS if it is a known weak point on that model.</li>\r\n                        </ol>\r\n                        <h2>Network attacks you can name</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>DoS / DDoS</strong> flood a service with traffic or requests so legitimate users cannot get through—attacks <strong>availability</strong>. Mitigation includes ISP scrubbing, rate limits, redundant capacity, and planning.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>MITM</strong> (man-in-the-middle) intercepts or alters traffic between two parties—public open Wi-Fi plus fake captive portals is a classic setup. <strong>HTTPS</strong> and <strong>VPN</strong> reduce readability of payloads on the wire, but users must still verify certificates and avoid bad proxies.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Spoofing</strong> forges sender identity (email “from” address, caller ID, fake websites). <strong>Replay</strong> resends captured legitimate packets—protocols use nonces/timestamps to fight this at higher levels.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Email and messaging hygiene</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>SMTP</strong> sends; <strong>POP3</strong> and <strong>IMAP</strong> receive—prefer IMAP for multi-device sync. <strong>SPAM</strong> is unsolicited bulk mail; filters score content and reputation. <strong>Phishing</strong> often arrives as email or SMS with malicious links/attachments. <strong>SPF/DKIM/DMARC</strong> are sender-authentication technologies that reduce forged mail—know them as “help prove mail really came from that domain.”</p>\r\n                        <p>Never enable macros on unexpected Office files. Block <strong>.exe</strong> attachments at the mail gateway when policy allows; train users to verify invoices and HR requests through known channels.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Certificates, hashing, and encryption vocabulary</h2>\r\n                        <p>A <strong>digital certificate</strong> binds a public key to an identity (website, organization) signed by a <strong>Certificate Authority (CA)</strong>. Browsers trust built-in root CAs and validate chains during HTTPS. A <strong>hash</strong> (e.g., SHA-256) produces a fixed-length fingerprint of data—tiny changes produce totally different hashes, useful for integrity checks of downloads.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Symmetric</strong> encryption uses one shared secret (fast, used for bulk data). <strong>Asymmetric</strong> uses key pairs (public encrypt / private decrypt, or signing)—slower, used to bootstrap symmetric keys (as in TLS handshakes). You will not implement these on Tech+; you will classify scenarios.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Physical security and insider risk</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Tailgating</strong> follows an authorized person through a door—defeat with badges, mantraps, and culture (“please badge in”). <strong>Clean desk</strong> hides sensitive papers. <strong>USB drops</strong> (malicious flash drives) exploit curiosity—disable AutoRun and use policy. <strong>Screen privacy filters</strong> reduce off-angle viewing; <strong>Win+L</strong> / lock when stepping away.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Insider threats</strong> include disgruntled employees and compromised accounts—logging, least privilege, and separation of duties limit damage.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-recap\">\r\n                            <div class=\"lh-tg-recap-head\">Exam Essentials — security threats &amp; best practices</div>\r\n                            <h4>Threats, CIA, privacy (Ch.10)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li>Data is an <strong>asset</strong>—used to improve products, target customers, or sold; <strong>critical</strong> data needs strongest controls.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Big data</strong> = large, often unstructured datasets analyzed for patterns.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Confidentiality</strong> attacks: snooping, eavesdropping, wiretapping, social engineering, dumpster diving.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Integrity</strong> attacks: on-path, replay, impersonation, unauthorized alteration.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Availability</strong> attacks: DoS, outages, power loss, hardware failure/destruction.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>PII</strong> privacy; <strong>GDPR</strong> (EU); US <strong>Privacy Act</strong> + state laws; <strong>cookie consent</strong> before storing cookies.</li>\r\n                                <li>Social media: public vs friends-only expectations.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Authentication factors:</strong> password, PIN, OTP, software/hardware tokens, biometrics, location, security questions.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>SSO</strong> one credential set across systems.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Permissions</strong> bundle privileges (read vs edit).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Least privilege</strong> minimum access needed.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Accounting</strong> via logs, location tracking, browser history.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Nonrepudiation:</strong> video, biometrics, signatures, receipts.</li>\r\n                                <li>Malware family: viruses, worms, trojans, adware, spyware, ransomware, rootkits, backdoors, spam, password attacks.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <h4>Hardening, passwords, encryption, browsing (Ch.11)</h4>\r\n                            <ul>\r\n                                <li><strong>Device hardening:</strong> anti-malware + software firewall; non-default passwords; safe browsing; patch; trusted download sources; remove/disable unused software &amp; services; disable <strong>AutoPlay</strong>.</li>\r\n                                <li>Physical: laptop <strong>cable lock</strong>; <strong>Ctrl+Alt+Del</strong> / lock when leaving seat.</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>Encryption at rest</strong> scrambles data so even local admins can’t read others’ encrypted files (user-specific).</li>\r\n                                <li><strong>In transit:</strong> corporate email often encrypted; <strong>HTTPS</strong>; <strong>VPN</strong> for remote workers—client makes remote LAN look local.</li>\r\n                                <li>Passwords: change defaults; complexity; confidential; rotate; no reuse across sites or recycled old passwords.</li>\r\n                                <li>Browser: latest version; manage extensions; disable risky <strong>Autofill</strong>; security settings; cookies/history hygiene.</li>\r\n                                <li>Secure site: URL starts with <code>https://</code>.</li>\r\n                                <li>Policies: acceptable use, confidentiality handling, security awareness training.</li>\r\n                            </ul>\r\n                            <p class=\"src\">Topic recap for CIA, threats, privacy, hardening, and safe computing.</p>\r\n                        </div></div>","tech-06":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><h2>Networking basics</h2>\r\n                        <p>Networks are layered. At the physical layer you have cables and radios; above that, devices speak <strong>Ethernet frames</strong> addressed by <strong>MAC</strong>. At layer 3, <strong>IP addresses</strong> let routers move packets across different subnets and across the world. Two machines on the same subnet talk locally (often via switch); to reach another network, traffic goes to a <strong>default gateway</strong>—usually your router’s LAN address.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Ports</strong> (like <code>443</code>) are not jacks on the wall; they are numbers in TCP/UDP headers telling the OS which application should receive the segment. That is how one public IP can host web, mail, and VPN—each service listens on its own port.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>LAN</strong> — Single site or logical grouping (home, office floor). <strong>WAN</strong> — Connects distant sites; the Internet is a public WAN. <strong>Router</strong> — Routes between subnets/networks; often includes NAT for home. <strong>Switch</strong> — Forwards frames inside a LAN by MAC. <strong>Modem</strong> — Terminates ISP link (cable/fiber/DSL). <strong>WAP</strong> — Adds Wi-Fi access to the wired LAN.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>DHCP</strong> saves you from typing IP, mask, gateway, and DNS by hand—essential when laptops roam. <strong>DNS</strong> is the phone book: humans remember <code>example.com</code>; stacks need numbers. If DNS breaks, “the Internet looks down” even when raw IP still works—a classic isolate-the-layer lesson.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Client-server</strong> centralizes services (files, authentication, databases). <strong>Peer-to-peer</strong> treats nodes as equals—simple shares, some updates, but harder to secure and audit at scale.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-example\">\r\n                            <strong>Mini scenario:</strong> PC gets 169.254.x.x APIPA address → likely no DHCP reachability (bad Wi-Fi, rogue switch, DHCP server down). PC gets correct IP but cannot browse → try ping gateway, then ping 8.8.8.8, then DNS—each step tells you which layer failed.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Internet access types &amp; Wi-Fi standards</h2>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Fiber</strong> — Glass, very high bandwidth, low latency; great for symmetric speeds.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cable</strong> — Shared neighborhood segment; fast downloads; upload varies.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>DSL</strong> — Copper phone lines; distance-sensitive.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cellular (LTE/5G)</strong> — Mobile broadband; hotspot tethering.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <p>Each Wi-Fi generation improved encoding, channel width, and multi-user tricks. <strong>802.11n</strong> brought better 2.4/5 GHz speeds; <strong>802.11ac</strong> pushed 5 GHz wave-2 gear; <strong>802.11ax</strong> (Wi-Fi 6) targets dense environments; <strong>Wi-Fi 6E</strong> adds <strong>6 GHz</strong> spectrum where regulators allow—more clean air, but shorter reach through walls. <strong>2.4 GHz</strong> is crowded (Bluetooth, microwaves, old gear) but travels farther; <strong>5 GHz</strong> offers more throughput with less range; <strong>6 GHz</strong> is premium spectrum for new laptops and phones.</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>Fiber vs cable vs DSL vs cellular</strong> is an economics and physics story: fiber offers huge symmetrical bandwidth and low latency when deployed; cable shares neighborhood coax; DSL degrades with copper length; cellular roams but faces towers and data caps.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Cloud &amp; virtualization</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Virtualization</strong> decouples operating systems from bare metal. A <strong>hypervisor</strong> schedules CPU time, carves RAM, and virtualizes disks and NICs so each guest OS believes it owns hardware. That enables <strong>snapshots</strong>, <strong>live migration</strong> in data centers, and “rent a VM by the hour.”</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Model</th><th>You manage</th><th>Vendor manages</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>IaaS</strong></td><td>OS, apps, data, some networking</td><td>Servers, storage, hypervisor, data center</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>PaaS</strong></td><td>App and data</td><td>Runtime, middleware, scaling, patching platform</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>SaaS</strong></td><td>Your content/config</td><td>Entire application stack</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p><strong>On-premises</strong> — You own the gear in your building. <strong>Public cloud</strong> — Shared provider (AWS/Azure/GCP style). <strong>Hybrid</strong> — Mix (e.g. AD on-prem + SaaS email). <strong>Hypervisor</strong> — Software/firmware that runs virtual machines: <strong>Type 1</strong> (bare-metal, ESXi/Hyper-V on server) vs <strong>Type 2</strong> (hosted on top of an OS, e.g. desktop VM apps).</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>IaaS</strong> is “give me VMs and disks”; you still patch the OS. <strong>PaaS</strong> is “give me a runtime and database service”; you focus on code. <strong>SaaS</strong> is “give me Gmail/Teams/365”—you configure, you do not compile the stack. The exam wants you to place a scenario into the right bucket: who patches the database engine? Who owns physical servers?</p>\r\n                        <h2>Basic maintenance &amp; support mindset</h2>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>Preventive</strong> — Dust filters, cable strain relief, surge/UPS, scheduled backups, patch Tuesday cadence.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>ESD</strong> — Use anti-static strap/mat when handling boards; discharge before touching internals.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Environmental</strong> — Heat kills; ensure intake/exhaust clear; laptops on hard surfaces.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <h2>RAID concepts (recognition level)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>RAID</strong> combines multiple disks for speed, redundancy, or both—usually via a hardware controller or OS software RAID. Tech+ expects vocabulary, not calculator math.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Level</th><th>Idea</th><th>Trade-off</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>0</strong> (striping)</td><td>Data split across disks—fast reads/writes</td><td><strong>No redundancy</strong>; one disk dies → data loss</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>1</strong> (mirroring)</td><td>Two disks hold the same data</td><td>Survives one disk failure; costs 50% capacity</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>5</strong></td><td>Striping + distributed parity</td><td>Survives one disk failure; needs at least three disks</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>10</strong> (1+0)</td><td>Mirror of stripes</td><td>Performance + redundancy; needs at least four disks</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p>Exam distractors may offer “RAID 0 is safest”—false. “RAID 1 is for redundancy”—true. NAS appliances and servers advertise these modes in their GUIs.</p>\r\n                        <h2>IPv4 essentials for workstations</h2>\r\n                        <p>You do not subnet for Tech+, but you must recognize <strong>normal vs broken</strong> addresses. <strong>Private</strong> ranges (not routed on the public Internet): <code>10.0.0.0/8</code>, <code>172.16.0.0–172.31.255.255</code>, <code>192.168.0.0/16</code>. Home routers usually hand out <code>192.168.x.x</code>. <strong>APIPA</strong> <code>169.254.0.0/16</code> means “I could not get DHCP”—check cable, Wi-Fi, or DHCP server. <strong>Loopback</strong> <code>127.0.0.1</code> tests the local TCP/IP stack.</p>\r\n                        <p>A <strong>subnet mask</strong> (often <code>255.255.255.0</code> on small LANs) tells the host which bits identify the network vs the host. The <strong>default gateway</strong> is the router’s LAN IP on your subnet—traffic to other subnets goes there.</p>\r\n                        <h2>Well-known ports (memorize the hits)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Ports</strong> are application endpoints on top of IP. Firewalls filter by port; exams love “which service uses which port?”</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Port(s)</th><th>Protocol / service</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>20/21</td><td>FTP (data / control)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>22</td><td>SSH (secure shell)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>23</td><td>Telnet (insecure—avoid)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>25</td><td>SMTP (mail send)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>53</td><td>DNS</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>67/68</td><td>DHCP server / client</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>80</td><td>HTTP</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>110</td><td>POP3 (mail receive)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>143</td><td>IMAP (mail receive)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>443</td><td>HTTPS (HTTP over TLS)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>445</td><td>SMB / Windows file sharing</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td>3389</td><td>RDP (Remote Desktop)</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <h2>Acronym clusters (study guide Ch.7)</h2><div class=\"lh-tg-summary\">\r\n                            <h3>Acronyms &amp; drills</h3>\r\n                            <p>Filter the table, mark review objectives below, then run matching rounds until definitions feel instant.</p>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>How to learn acronyms as language, not flashcards alone</h2>\r\n                        <p>Three-letter acronyms stick when they sit inside a <em>sentence you could explain to a friend</em>. For each term, ask: <strong>What layer is it?</strong> (hardware, OS, network, app). <strong>What problem does it solve?</strong> <strong>What breaks if it is misconfigured?</strong> Example: <strong>DHCP</strong> is not “a magic setting”—it is how a host learns IP, mask, gateway, and DNS without manual typing. <strong>DNS</strong> is not “the Internet”—it is name resolution; break DNS and IP-only tests still work.</p>\r\n                        <p>Use the searchable table below as your <strong>primary</strong> glossary—definitions here are written to match what Tech+ expects. Networking, storage, and security acronyms (TLS, VPN, WPA, DNS, DHCP, NAS, UPS…) recycle across every CompTIA fundamentals exam—prioritize those clusters first.</p>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-key\">\r\n                            <strong>Study tactic:</strong> One pass sorted A–Z (this table), one pass using <strong>filter</strong> by topic keyword (<code>wireless</code>, <code>mail</code>, <code>disk</code>), then daily <strong>matching rounds</strong> until you stop guessing.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>High-yield clusters (memorize as groups)</h2>\r\n                        <p>Instead of random letters, learn <strong>stories</strong> for each cluster below—exam items often pull two terms from the same cluster as answer vs distractor.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Cluster</th><th>Terms to tie together</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Getting on the network</strong></td><td><strong>NIC</strong> hardware → <strong>MAC</strong> Layer-2 address → <strong>IP</strong> Layer-3 address → <strong>DHCP</strong> auto-config → <strong>DNS</strong> names → <strong>default gateway</strong> for other subnets</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Wireless security timeline</strong></td><td><strong>WEP</strong> (broken, legacy) → <strong>WPA</strong> → <strong>WPA2</strong> (common) → <strong>WPA3</strong> (current gen); pair with <strong>SSID</strong> and <strong>PSK</strong> vs enterprise auth</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Remote access &amp; privacy</strong></td><td><strong>VPN</strong> tunnel → <strong>RDP</strong> for Windows remote desktop → <strong>SSH</strong> for encrypted shell → <strong>HTTPS</strong> for web → <strong>TLS</strong> under the hood</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Mail flow</strong></td><td><strong>SMTP</strong> send → <strong>POP3</strong> / <strong>IMAP</strong> receive → ports <strong>25 / 110 / 143 / 587 / 993 / 995</strong> (know SMTP + 443/HTTPS for webmail)</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Storage &amp; speed</strong></td><td><strong>HDD</strong> platters → <strong>SSD</strong> flash → <strong>NVMe</strong> on PCIe → <strong>SATA</strong> older bus → <strong>NAS</strong> network share → <strong>UPS</strong> protects uptime</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Cloud models</strong></td><td><strong>IaaS</strong> VMs → <strong>PaaS</strong> runtime → <strong>SaaS</strong> finished app; deployment: <strong>public</strong> / <strong>private</strong> / <strong>hybrid</strong></td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Threats &amp; defense</strong></td><td><strong>CIA</strong> goals → <strong>phishing</strong> / <strong>malware</strong> / <strong>ransomware</strong> → <strong>MFA</strong> → <strong>least privilege</strong> → <strong>patching</strong> → <strong>backup</strong> / <strong>3-2-1</strong></td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-note\">\r\n                            <strong>Exam night:</strong> Skim this cluster table, then run two <strong>matching rounds</strong>. If you miss an acronym, filter the main table for one keyword from the cluster and read the full definition once.\r\n                        </div></div>","tech-07":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><h2>Cloud &amp; virtualization</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>Virtualization</strong> decouples operating systems from bare metal. A <strong>hypervisor</strong> schedules CPU time, carves RAM, and virtualizes disks and NICs so each guest OS believes it owns hardware. That enables <strong>snapshots</strong>, <strong>live migration</strong> in data centers, and “rent a VM by the hour.”</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Model</th><th>You manage</th><th>Vendor manages</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>IaaS</strong></td><td>OS, apps, data, some networking</td><td>Servers, storage, hypervisor, data center</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>PaaS</strong></td><td>App and data</td><td>Runtime, middleware, scaling, patching platform</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>SaaS</strong></td><td>Your content/config</td><td>Entire application stack</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p><strong>On-premises</strong> — You own the gear in your building. <strong>Public cloud</strong> — Shared provider (AWS/Azure/GCP style). <strong>Hybrid</strong> — Mix (e.g. AD on-prem + SaaS email). <strong>Hypervisor</strong> — Software/firmware that runs virtual machines: <strong>Type 1</strong> (bare-metal, ESXi/Hyper-V on server) vs <strong>Type 2</strong> (hosted on top of an OS, e.g. desktop VM apps).</p>\r\n                        <p><strong>IaaS</strong> is “give me VMs and disks”; you still patch the OS. <strong>PaaS</strong> is “give me a runtime and database service”; you focus on code. <strong>SaaS</strong> is “give me Gmail/Teams/365”—you configure, you do not compile the stack. The exam wants you to place a scenario into the right bucket: who patches the database engine? Who owns physical servers?</p>\r\n                        </div>","tech-09":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><h2>Backups: scope and location</h2>\r\n                        <p>Backups are an insurance policy—useless if you never test a restore. <strong>Ransomware</strong> made offline or immutable copies famous: if your only backup is a mapped drive letter, malware encrypts it too. <strong>File-level</strong> backup protects Sally’s Documents; <strong>image backup</strong> captures OS + apps so you can rebuild a machine after disk death without two days of reinstalling.</p>\r\n                        <p>Local copies are fast to restore; off-site/cloud copies survive building loss. Rotate media, encrypt sensitive archives, and document <em>who</em> is allowed to run restores (least privilege applies to backup consoles too).</p>\r\n                        <ul>\r\n                            <li><strong>File / folder backup</strong> — User documents, photos, databases export—fast restore of data but not full OS state.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>System / image backup</strong> — Snapshot of OS, apps, drivers—bare-metal or full machine restore.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Local</strong> — External drive, NAS on LAN; quick restores.</li>\r\n                            <li><strong>Cloud / off-site</strong> — Survives fire/theft; watch encryption and retention policies.</li>\r\n                        </ul>\r\n                        <div class=\"lh-tg-key\">\r\n                            <strong>3-2-1 rule (classic):</strong> At least <strong>three</strong> copies, on <strong>two</strong> different media, with <strong>one</strong> off-site. Test a restore before you need it.\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        <h2>Full vs incremental vs differential backups</h2>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Type</th><th>What is copied</th><th>Restore complexity</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Full</strong></td><td>Everything selected (whole system or dataset)</td><td>Easiest—restore one full set</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Incremental</strong></td><td>Only files changed since the <em>last backup of any kind</em></td><td>May need full + every incremental in order</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>Differential</strong></td><td>Changes since the <em>last full</em></td><td>Restore full + latest differential</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p>Cloud sync (OneDrive/Google Drive) is <strong>not</strong> a full image backup—it may not recover OS state, and ransomware can encrypt synced copies if versioning is weak.</p>\r\n                        </div>","tech-18":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source lh-md-topic-source\">Tech+ topic notes (bundled here). For quizzes, drills, and the acronym table, use the separate <strong>Tech+ Study Guide</strong> HTML from your materials if you have it.</p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-chapter-markdown\"><h2>RAID concepts (recognition level)</h2>\r\n                        <p><strong>RAID</strong> combines multiple disks for speed, redundancy, or both—usually via a hardware controller or OS software RAID. Tech+ expects vocabulary, not calculator math.</p>\r\n                        <table>\r\n                            <tr><th>Level</th><th>Idea</th><th>Trade-off</th></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>0</strong> (striping)</td><td>Data split across disks—fast reads/writes</td><td><strong>No redundancy</strong>; one disk dies → data loss</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>1</strong> (mirroring)</td><td>Two disks hold the same data</td><td>Survives one disk failure; costs 50% capacity</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>5</strong></td><td>Striping + distributed parity</td><td>Survives one disk failure; needs at least three disks</td></tr>\r\n                            <tr><td><strong>10</strong> (1+0)</td><td>Mirror of stripes</td><td>Performance + redundancy; needs at least four disks</td></tr>\r\n                        </table>\r\n                        <p>Exam distractors may offer “RAID 0 is safest”—false. “RAID 1 is for redundancy”—true. NAS appliances and servers advertise these modes in their GUIs.</p>\r\n                        </div>"};
// learn-hub: touch
